    "caption": "Carrying its house on its back, leaving a silver trail.",
    "shortDescription": "A snail's shell isn't just a home it carries around — the shell is actually part of its body, grown by a special organ and connected to its organs inside. It makes its own slime to glide on, and that slime is good enough to let a snail travel safely across a razor blade without being cut. Fun fact: Snails have thousands of tiny teeth arranged on a tongue-like ribbon called a radula, which they use to scrape food off surfaces."
